So in this case, what we can do is run over the iris Spark table that we previously copied

00:06:29.019 --> 00:06:30.459
into Spark.

00:06:30.459 --> 00:06:33.940
We can run Spark apply with a custom function.

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:41.140
And what is important here to notice is that on the right side, the S apply from that is

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:44.260
applying the jitter function over each column.

00:06:44.260 --> 00:06:46.100
This is R code, right?

00:06:46.100 --> 00:06:51.660
This is code that we're familiar with, and it's R code that is executing across the cluster.

00:06:51.660 --> 00:06:59.820
So very easy kind of like entry point to reuse the skills that we already know in R.

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:05.779
And the second use case is basically as a way to complement R. By this, what I mean

00:07:05.779 --> 00:07:10.239
is that Spark is a rich ecosystem where you can do a lot of things.

00:07:10.339 --> 00:07:19.200
But there's still a lot of packages on the R community that provide a lot of value, right?

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:24.720
And for instance, one case is that at times you might want to run a linear model, a linear

00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:31.119
regression over Spark, and MLE or H2O might be just what you need.

00:07:31.119 --> 00:07:37.500
In some other cases, you might want to use the actual linear regression for a subset

00:07:37.500 --> 00:07:45.700
of the data that would match better the expectations that you have from the model that is created.

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:49.420
So for that particular case, you can also use Spark apply.

00:07:49.420 --> 00:07:57.739
In this case, we're using the broom package to tidy the linear model that we're creating.

00:07:57.739 --> 00:08:03.899
But the linear model that is being executed, it's exactly the same linear model that you

00:08:03.899 --> 00:08:05.100
would run in R.

00:08:05.540 --> 00:08:14.339
It just happens to be the case that is being executed over a dataset that it's large enough

00:08:14.339 --> 00:08:17.220
that it's worth splitting into smaller pieces.

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:24.579
So we're running a group by query here over the species, which means that basically we're

00:08:24.579 --> 00:08:30.600
asking Spark to split the dataset into groups by species.

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:37.039
Something worth noting in this, in the concept of Spark apply, is that the function that

00:08:37.039 --> 00:08:46.719
you provide, it's gonna, the parameter that it gets, which is a data frame, and the result

00:08:46.719 --> 00:08:52.159
of this function that Spark apply expects should be also a data frame.

00:08:52.159 --> 00:08:56.440
I've definitely got, we definitely got a bunch of questions of like, hey, Spark apply is

00:08:56.440 --> 00:09:02.080
not working appropriately, and a lot of them were mostly related with not returning the

00:09:02.080 --> 00:09:07.960
correct data type, which should be a data frame from all the functions that you write

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:10.239
on Spark apply.

