So those are our two main use cases, and what I wanna talk a little bit is give you an overview

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.239
of how Spark apply actually works.

00:09:24.239 --> 00:09:31.400
So this diagram shows how your Spark cluster probably looks like today.

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:38.719
If you're already a Sparkly R user, what you should probably, what you're probably doing

00:09:38.719 --> 00:09:45.200
today is you have a machine, which is usually your gateway into the cluster, that might

00:09:45.200 --> 00:09:52.479
also be the master node for this cluster that basically has R, the R runtime installed,

00:09:53.479 --> 00:09:58.479
where you are already using Sparkly R and several other packages from this machine.

00:09:58.479 --> 00:10:04.599
It is usually the case that RStudio or Shiny server would be installed on this machine,

00:10:04.599 --> 00:10:14.559
so kind of like this, this should be a diagram that looks familiar to you, that you use on

00:10:14.559 --> 00:10:16.599
your day to day.

00:10:16.599 --> 00:10:22.840
So the first important thing to understand for Spark apply is that it requires a change

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:32.640
in your cluster, and by this what I mean is that it is your responsibility, Sparkly R

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:40.159
won't help you with this particular step, to install R on each worker node.

00:10:40.159 --> 00:10:45.559
This is usually a pretty straightforward step, there's usually, in my demo for instance,

00:10:45.559 --> 00:10:50.599
I provisioned my cluster with script, and basically I just had to add one more line

00:10:50.599 --> 00:10:55.940
to say, hey, when you're provisioning this cluster, make sure that R is installed in

00:10:55.940 --> 00:10:58.359
each worker node.

00:10:58.359 --> 00:11:03.559
What is important to notice, because if you have a cluster that looks more like this,

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:07.799
you won't be able to use Spark apply, it is the case that you will be able to use any

00:11:07.799 --> 00:11:13.739
of the Sparkly R functionality that you already know and are familiar with.

00:11:13.739 --> 00:11:17.380
But if you want to use Spark apply, you need to get R installed on each worker node, and

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:25.539
this really depends on each different clusters, require different ways of installing R on

00:11:25.539 --> 00:11:27.659
each node.

00:11:27.659 --> 00:11:35.179
Service providers like for instance, Databricks already support execution of R codes across

00:11:35.179 --> 00:11:39.140
their clusters, so you wouldn't have to worry about this.

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:43.859
So the next step is, okay, what happens when we actually run Spark apply?

00:11:43.859 --> 00:11:50.780
So you would run Spark apply from R studio, and in this case, we're running the same function

00:11:50.780 --> 00:11:57.619
that we looked at, which is just using jitter to add some noise into our dataset.

00:11:57.619 --> 00:12:04.460
And what happens there is on the first call, well, the first time that a worker node needs

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:13.419
to make use of this distributed functionality, what Sparkly R with Spark are going to do

00:12:13.419 --> 00:12:18.979
is they're going to deploy all your packages that you're currently using to each worker

00:12:18.979 --> 00:12:20.479
node.

00:12:20.479 --> 00:12:25.900
So just to be clear here, you don't need to ask your system administrators to manage packages

00:12:25.900 --> 00:12:28.260
while you're using Spark apply.

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:35.580
Spark apply will do that for you while you're executing, in this case, you know, pretty

00:12:35.580 --> 00:12:42.020
small closure, would basically deploy all those packages for you to each worker node.

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:46.739
It does take a little bit of time, we'll see an example of this, it depends on your cluster,

00:12:46.739 --> 00:12:51.599
but it's not bad, and you get basically all the functionality, the rich functionality

00:12:51.599 --> 00:12:56.580
that you would expect to use in R on each of the worker nodes.

00:12:56.580 --> 00:13:02.580
And then, well, last but again, not least, your code is going to be executing over each

00:13:02.580 --> 00:13:03.580
worker node.

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:06.619
So in this case, again, is the jitter function.

00:13:06.619 --> 00:13:13.900
What each worker node is going to get is this code with a subset of the dataset.

00:13:13.900 --> 00:13:18.940
The way Spark works is based on RDD partitions.

00:13:18.940 --> 00:13:26.219
So whenever you get a partition, that is basically a set of rows on your dataset, we are going

00:13:26.219 --> 00:13:32.340
to apply the function that you give us through Sparkly R in each node, and then Spark will

00:13:32.340 --> 00:13:36.619
collect the results and put them back all together for you.

00:13:36.619 --> 00:13:45.020
So in general, this kind of like covers how Spark, Spark apply works, and definitely if

00:13:45.020 --> 00:13:49.940
you have questions, please write them down and we'll address them.

